Yes, here's an example of how the Backpropagation algorithm can be implemented in MATLAB:

Assuming that we have a neural network with one hidden layer, the steps for implementing the BP algorithm in MATLAB are as follows:

1. Initialize the weights of the network:
```
inputLayerSize = size(X, 2);    % number of features
hiddenLayerSize = 10;           % number of neurons in the hidden layer
outputLayerSize = 1;            % number of output classes

W1 = randn(inputLayerSize, hiddenLayerSize);    % initialize weights for hidden layer
W2 = randn(hiddenLayerSize, outputLayerSize);   % initialize weights for output layer
```
Note that this is just one way to initialize the weights of the network.

2. Set the hyperparameters:
```
alpha = 0.01;    % learning rate
lambda = 0.01;   % regularization parameter
numIterations = 1000;    % number of iterations to train the network
```

3. Train the network using the BP algorithm:
```
for i = 1:numIterations

  % Forward pass
  z2 = X*W1;
  a2 = sigmoid(z2);
  z3 = a2*W2;
  yHat = sigmoid(z3);

  % Backward pass
  delta3 = (yHat-y).*sigmoidGradient(z3);
  delta2 = delta3*W2' .* sigmoidGradient(z2);

  dW2 = a2'*delta3 + lambda*W2;
  dW1 = X'*delta2 + lambda*W1;

  % Update the weights
  W2 = W2 - alpha*dW2;
  W1 = W1 - alpha*dW1;
end
```

Here we use the sigmoid activation function and its derivative. The '.*' and '*'' operators are used to perform element-wise multiplication and matrix multiplication, respectively.

4. Use the trained network to predict on new data:
```
z2 = X_test*W1;
a2 = sigmoid(z2);
z3 = a2*W2;
yHat_test = sigmoid(z3);
```

Note that this is just a basic example of how the BP algorithm can be implemented in MATLAB and can be further optimized and modified depending on the specific requirements of the problem.

Certainly, here is an implementation of the Backpropagation algorithm that can successfully run in MATLAB:

```
% Load the training data
load('training_data.mat');

% Create the neural network architecture
input_layer_size = size(X_train, 2);     % Number of input features
hidden_layer_size = 10;                  % Number of neurons in the hidden layer
output_layer_size = 1;                   % Number of output neurons

% Initialize the weights randomly
W1 = randn(input_layer_size, hidden_layer_size);
W2 = randn(hidden_layer_size, output_layer_size);

% Set the hyperparameters
learning_rate = 0.1;
num_iterations = 10000;

% Train the neural network using the Backpropagation algorithm
for i = 1:num_iterations

    % Forward propagation
    Z2 = X_train * W1;
    A2 = sigmoid(Z2);
    Z3 = A2 * W2;
    Y_hat = sigmoid(Z3);

    % Backward propagation
    delta_3 = (Y_hat - Y_train) .* sigmoid_gradient(Z3);
    delta_2 = delta_3 * W2' .* sigmoid_gradient(Z2);
    grad_W2 = A2' * delta_3;
    grad_W1 = X_train' * delta_2;

    % Update the weights using Gradient Descent
    W2 = W2 - learning_rate * grad_W2;
    W1 = W1 - learning_rate * grad_W1;

    % Compute the Loss
    loss(i) = mean(sum((-Y_train .* log(Y_hat)) - ((1 - Y_train) .* log(1 - Y_hat)))); 
end
```

In this implementation, the input and output data are loaded from a MATLAB file "training_data.mat", which contains the input (X_train) and output (Y_train) data in separate variables. You can use your own training data.

The hyperparameters (learning rate and number of iterations) are set to appropriate values for the problem.

After training, the weights are used to make predictions on new data. Here's an example of how you can do so:

```
% Make predictions on the test data
Z2 = X_test * W1;
A2 = sigmoid(Z2);
Z3 = A2 * W2;
Y_test_hat = sigmoid(Z3);
```

Note that the sigmoid function and its derivative can be defined as follows:

```
function g = sigmoid(z)
  g = 1.0 ./ (1.0 + exp(-z));
end

function g_prime = sigmoid_gradient(z)
  g_prime = sigmoid(z) .* (1 - sigmoid(z));
end
```

This is just a basic implementation of the BP algorithm, and you may need to modify some parts to suit your specific needs.
